: bridging beltway and ivory tower? -- tNon-university research institutes: between basic research, knowledge transfer to the public and policy analysis -- tThe role of policy analysis in teaching political science at German universities -- tAcademics and policy analysis: tension between epistemic and practical concerns -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis comprehensive study, part of the International Library of Policy Analysis, brings together for the first time a systemic overview of policy analysis activities in Germany. Written by leading experts in the field – including informed practitioners – it outlines the development of the discipline, identifies its role in academic education and research, and examines its styles and methods. The book also focuses on the role of policy analysis for governments and parliaments, for parties, social partners, and interest groups. By offering a rich and timely analysis of policy analysis in Germany, this book is a valuable resource for academic exchange and for teaching, particularly in the fields of political science, social sciences, economics and geography. Moreover, by its broad, comprehensive understanding of ‘policy analysis’, the book will be of practical relevance and shape the debate for the future development of policy analysis in Germany and the different spheres where it is practised.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aPolicy scienceszGermany. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aBandelow, Nils C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeyme, Klaus von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiegelbauer, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlum, Sonja, econtr